answers.body_markdown:
## The problem you are experiencing

Note that you have nested loops.
```java
do{
    while(CardDealt &lt;= numCards){
        //...
        response = scan.next().charAt(0);
    }
} while(response == &#39;Y&#39;); 
```

So, you are only looping until all cards are dealt and only then checking the response.

Instead, you can integrate the `CardDealt &lt;= numCards` check in the `do while`-loop:

```java
do{
    //...
    response = scan.next().charAt(0);
} while(response == &#39;Y&#39; &amp;&amp; CardDealt &lt;= numCards); 
```
This will check the response in each iteration and stop the loop if it isn&#39;t `Y`.

## Other issues/improvements

### re-creating `Scanner`
Also, I would not recommend you to create a new `Scanner` in each iteration. Instead, you can reuse the same scanner throughout your whole program:
```java
Scanner scan = new Scanner(System.in);//before the loop
do{
    //...
    //also do not create the scanner here
    response = scan.next().charAt(0);
} while(response == &#39;Y&#39; &amp;&amp; CardDealt &lt;= numCards); 
```

### drawing one card too much
As [outlined in the comments](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/75863701/java-do-while-loop-continues-even-though-the-condition-is-false/75863734?noredirect=1#comment133816222_75863734), you are also drawing one card too much by also drawing when 52 cards have already been dealt (this is called in off-by-one error). Instead of `CardDealt &lt;= numCards`, you would need to use `CardDealt &lt; numCards` (only take another card if LESS THAN 52 cards have been taken).

```java
Scanner scan = new Scanner(System.in);//before the loop
do{
    //...
    //also do not create the scanner here
    response = scan.next().charAt(0);
} while(response == &#39;Y&#39; &amp;&amp; CardDealt &lt; numCards); //&lt; instead of &lt;= here
```

### taking cards with repetition

As [Ole V.V.](https://stackoverflow.com/users/5772882/ole-v-v) [mentions in the comments](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/75863701/java-do-while-loop-continues-even-though-the-condition-is-false/75863734?noredirect=1#comment133815810_75863734), your code could pick the same card multiple times.

If you are able to use the collection API (which is unlikely if you cannot use arrays),you can get around that issue by collecting all cards in a list, shuffle it and then remove one each time.

```java
public record Card(String name, String suit){}//or similar
```

then, you can create a list of cards using loops:
```java
List&lt;String&gt; cardNames=List.of(&quot;Ace&quot;, &quot;2&quot;, &quot;3&quot;, &quot;4&quot;, &quot;5&quot;, &quot;6&quot;, &quot;7&quot;, &quot;8&quot;, &quot;9&quot;, &quot;10&quot;,  &quot;Jack&quot;, &quot;Queen&quot;, &quot;King&quot;);
List&lt;String&gt; suitNames=List.of(&quot;Diamonds&quot;,&quot;Clubs&quot;,&quot;Hearts&quot;,&quot;Spades&quot;);
List&lt;Card&gt; cards=new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

//go through all combinations of card and suit names
for(String cardName:cardNames){
    for(String suitName:suitNames){
        //add that as a card
        cards.add(new Card(cardName, suitName))
    }
}

//shuffle the list of cards
Collections.shuffle(cards);

//draw a card
//just do this every time you draw a card
int index=cards.size()-1;
Card card=cards.remove(index);

//check whether there are cards left
//!cards.isEmpty()
```

Putting it all together in your code:
```java
